# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: elm-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm was initially designed by Evan Czaplicki as his thesis in 2012.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] The first release of Elm came with many examples and an online editor that made it easy to try out in a web browser.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Czaplicki joined Prezi in 2013 to work on Elm, and in 2016 moved to NoRedInk as an Open Source Engineer, also starting the Elm Software Foundation.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] The initial implementation of the Elm compiler targets HyperText Markup Language (HTML), Cascading Style Sheets (CSS), and JavaScript.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] The set of core tools has continued to expand, now including a read–eval–print loop (REPL), package manager, time-travelling debugger, and installers for macOS and Windows.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm also has an ecosystem of community created libraries, and Ellie, an advanced online editor that allows saved work and including community libraries.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm has a small set of language constructs, including traditional if-expressions, let-expressions for storing local values, and case-expressions for pattern matching.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] As a functional language, it supports anonymous functions, functions as arguments, and functions can return functions, the latter often by partial application of curried functions.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Its semantics include immutable values, stateless functions, and static typing with type inference.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm programs render HTML through a virtual DOM, and may interoperate with other code by using "JavaScript as a service".
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] All values in Elm are immutable, meaning that a value cannot be modified after it is created.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm uses persistent data structures to implement its arrays, sets, and dictionaries in the standard library.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Type annotations are optional (due to type inference) but strongly encouraged.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Annotations exist on the line above the definition (unlike C-family languages where types and names are interspersed).
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm uses a single colon to mean "has type".
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Types include primitives like integers and strings, and basic data structures such as lists, tuples, and records.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Functions have types written with arrows, for example `round : Float -> Int`.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Custom types allow the programmer to create custom types to represent data in a way that matches the problem domain.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Types can refer to other types, for example a `List Int`.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Types are always capitalized; lowercase names are type variables.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] For example, a `List a` is a list of values of unknown type.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] It is the type of the empty list and of the argument to `List.length`, which is agnostic to the list's elements.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] There are a few special types that programmers create to interact with the Elm runtime.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] For example, `Html Msg` represents a (virtual) DOM tree whose event handlers all produce messages of type `Msg`.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Rather than allow any value to be implicitly nullable (such as JavaScript's `undefined` or a null pointer), Elm's standard library defines a `Maybe a` type.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Code that produces or handles an optional value does so explicitly using this type, and all other code is guaranteed a value of the claimed type is actually present.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm does not provide a mechanism to include custom types into these type classes or create new type classes (see Limits).
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm has a module system that allows users to break their code into smaller parts called modules.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Modules can hide implementation details such as helper functions, and group related code together.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Modules serve as a namespace for imported code, such as `Bitwise.and`.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Third party libraries (or packages) consist of one or more modules, and are available from the Elm Public Library.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] All libraries are versioned according to semver, which is enforced by the compiler and other tools.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] That is, removing a function or changing its type can only be done in a major release.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm uses an abstraction called ports to communicate with JavaScript.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] It allows values to flow in and out of Elm programs, making it possible to communicate between Elm and JavaScript.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm has a library called elm/html that a programmer can use to write HTML and CSS within Elm.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] It uses a virtual DOM approach to make updates efficient.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm does not officially support server-side development.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Czaplicki does consider it a primary goal, but public progress on this front has been slow.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Nevertheless, there are several independent projects which attempt to explore Elm on the backend.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] The primary full-stack Elm platform is Lamdera, an open-core "unfork" of Elm.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Czaplicki has also teased Elm Studio, a potential alternative to Lamdera, but it is not yet available to the public.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Czaplicki's demos seemingly use a future version of Elm that supports type-safe Postgres table generation.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] There is also speculation that that future versions of Elm would compile to C and use Emscripten to generate WASM, but this is unconfirmed by Czaplicki.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] For full-stack frameworks, as opposed to BaaS products, elm-pages is likely the most popular fully open-source option.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] It does not extend the Elm language (although it does use open-source components of the aforementioned Lamdera compiler), but rather runs the compiled JavaScript on Node.js.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] It also supports scripting using the `BackendTask` API.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] There is also Pine, an Elm to .NET compiler, which allows safe interop with C#, F#, and other CLR languages.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] There were also attempts in Elm versions prior to 0.19.0 to use the BEAM (Erlang virtual machine) to run Elm, but they are currently non-functional due to the removal of native code in 0.19.0 and changes to the package manager.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] One of the projects executed Elm directly on the environment, while another one compiled it to Elixir.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] The Elm Architecture is a software design pattern and as a TLA called TEA pattern for building interactive web applications.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm applications are naturally constructed in that way, but other projects may find the concept useful.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Those are the core of the Elm Architecture.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] For example, imagine an application that displays a number and a button that increments the number when pressed.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] In this case, all we need to store is one number, so our model can be as simple as `type alias Model = Int`.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] The `view` function would be defined with the `Html` library and display the number and button.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] For the number to be updated, we need to be able to send a message to the `update` function, which is done through a custom type such as `type Msg = Increase`.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] The `Increase` value is attached to the button defined in the `view` function such that when the button is clicked by a user, `Increase` is passed on to the `update` function, which can update the model by increasing the number.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] In the Elm Architecture, sending messages to `update` is the only way to change the state.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] In more sophisticated applications, messages may come from various sources: user interaction, initialization of the model, internal calls from `update`, subscriptions to external events (window resize, system clock, JavaScript interop...) and URL changes and requests.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] Elm does not support higher-kinded polymorphism, which related languages Haskell, Scala and PureScript offer, nor does Elm support the creation of type classes.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] This means that, for example, Elm does not have a generic `map` function which works across multiple data structures such as `List` and `Set`.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] In Elm, such functions are typically invoked qualified by their module name, for example calling `List.map` and `Set.map`.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] In Haskell or PureScript, there would be only one function `map`.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] This is a known feature request that is on Czaplicki's rough roadmap since at least 2015.
[src:elm-lang/elm-programming-language] On the other hand, implementations of TEA pattern in advanced languages like Scala does not suffer from such limitations and can benefit from Scala's type classes, type-level and kind-level programming constructs.
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] By the end I hope you will not only be able to create great web apps in Elm, but also understand the core ideas and patterns that make Elm nice to use.
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] If you are on the fence, I can safely guarantee that if you give Elm a shot and actually make a project in it, you will end up writing better JavaScript code.
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] The code can definitely look unfamiliar at first, so we will get into how this example works soon!
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] No combination of JS libraries can give you all of these guarantees.
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] They come from the design of the language itself!
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] And thanks to these guarantees, it is quite common for Elm programmers to say they never felt so **confident** while programming.
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] Confident to refactor thousands of lines.
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] But without the background anxiety that you missed something important!
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] I have put a huge emphasis on making Elm easy to learn and use, so all I ask is that you give Elm a shot and see what you think.
[src:elm-lang/guide-elm-lang-org] I hope you will be pleasantly surprised!
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] In computer science, **purely functional programming** usually designates a programming paradigm—a style of building the structure and elements of computer programs—that treats all computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] This style handles state changes without losing the referential transparency of the program expressions.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programming consists of ensuring that functions, inside the functional paradigm, will only depend on their arguments, regardless of any global or local state.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] A pure functional subroutine only has visibility of changes of state represented by state variables included in its scope.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] The exact difference between pure and impure functional programming is a matter of controversy.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Sabry's proposed definition of purity is that all common evaluation strategies (call-by-name, call-by-value, and call-by-need) produce the same result, ignoring strategies that error or diverge.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] A program is usually said to be functional when it uses some concepts of functional programming, such as first-class functions and higher-order functions.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] However, a first-class function need not be purely functional, as it may use techniques from the imperative paradigm, such as arrays or input/output methods that use mutable cells, which update their state as side effects.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] In fact, the earliest programming languages cited as being functional, IPL and Lisp, are both "impure" functional languages by Sabry's definition.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Each evaluation strategy which ends on a purely functional program returns the same result.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] In particular, it ensures that the programmer does not have to consider in which order programs are evaluated, since eager evaluation will return the same result as lazy evaluation.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] However, it is still possible that an eager evaluation may not terminate while the lazy evaluation of the same program halts.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] An advantage of this is that lazy evaluation can be implemented much more easily; as all expressions will return the same result at any moment (regardless of program state), their evaluation can be delayed as much as necessary.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] In a purely functional language, the only dependencies between computations are data dependencies, and computations are deterministic.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, to program in parallel, the programmer need only specify the pieces that should be computed in parallel, and the runtime can handle all other details such as distributing tasks to processors, managing synchronization and communication, and collecting garbage in parallel.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] This style of programming avoids common issues such as race conditions and deadlocks, but has less control than an imperative language.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] To ensure a speedup, the granularity of tasks must be carefully chosen to be neither too big nor too small.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] In theory, it is possible to use runtime profiling and compile-time analysis to judge whether introducing parallelism will speed up the program, and thus automatically parallelize purely functional programs.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] In practice, this has not been terribly successful, and fully automatic parallelization is not practical.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are persistent.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Persistency is required for functional programming; without it, the same computation could return different results.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Functional programming may use persistent non-purely functional data structures, while those data structures may not be used in purely functional programs.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way than their imperative counterparts.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] For example, array with constant-time access and update is a basic component of most imperative languages and many imperative data-structures, such as hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by map or random access list, which admits purely functional implementation, but the access and update time is logarithmic.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, purely functional data structures can be used in languages which are non-functional, but they may not be the most efficient tool available, especially if persistency is not required.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] In general, conversion of an imperative program to a purely functional one also requires ensuring that the formerly-mutable structures are now explicitly returned from functions that update them, a program structure called store-passing style.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] A purely functional language is a language which only admits purely functional programming.
[src:elm-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programs can however be written in languages which are not purely functional.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] A **single-page application** (**SPA**) is a web application or website that interacts with the user by dynamically rewriting the current web page with new data from the web server, instead of the default method of loading entire new pages.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] The goal is faster transitions that make the website feel more like a native app.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In a SPA, a page refresh never occurs; instead, all necessary HTML, JavaScript, and CSS code is either retrieved by the browser with a single page load, or the appropriate resources are dynamically loaded and added to the page as necessary, usually in response to user actions.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] The origins of the term *single-page application* are unclear, though the concept was discussed at least as early as 2003 by technology evangelists from Netscape.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Earlier forms were called rich web applications.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] JavaScript can be used in a web browser to display the user interface (UI), run application logic, and communicate with a web server.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Mature free libraries are available that support the building of a SPA, reducing the amount of JavaScript code developers have to write.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] There are various techniques available that enable the browser to retain a single page even when the application requires server communication.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] HTML authors can leverage element IDs to show or hide different sections of the HTML document.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Then, using CSS, authors can use the `:target` pseudo-class selector to only show the section of the page which the browser navigated to.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Web browser JavaScript frameworks and libraries, such as Angular, Ember.js, ExtJS, Knockout.js, Meteor.js, React, Vue.js, and Svelte have adopted SPA principles.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Aside from ExtJS, all of these are free.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] The following frameworks utilize WebAssembly or can build single-page applications (SPAs) with WebAssembly as a core technology or support mechanism.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] These frameworks enable high-performance and interactive client-side development, extending the SPA paradigm across languages and ecosystems.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] As of 2006, the most prominent technique used was Ajax.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Ajax involves using asynchronous requests to a server for XML or JSON data, such as with JavaScript's XMLHttpRequest or more modern `fetch()` (since 2017), or the deprecated ActiveX Object.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In contrast to the declarative approach of most SPA frameworks, with Ajax the website directly uses JavaScript or a JavaScript library such as jQuery to manipulate the DOM and edit HTML elements.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Ajax has further been popularized by libraries like jQuery, which provides a simpler syntax and normalizes Ajax behavior across different browsers which historically had varying behavior.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] WebSockets are a bidirectional real-time client-server communication technology that are part of the HTML specification.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] For real-time communication, their use is superior to Ajax in terms of performance and simplicity.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Server-sent events (SSEs) is a technique whereby servers can initiate data transmission to browser clients.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Once an initial connection has been established, an event stream remains open until closed by the client.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] SSEs are sent over traditional HTTP and have a variety of features that WebSockets lack by design such as automatic reconnection, event IDs, and the ability to send arbitrary events.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Although this method is outdated, asynchronous calls to the server may also be achieved using browser plug-in technologies such as Silverlight, Flash, or Java applets.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Requests to the server typically result in either raw data (e.g., XML or JSON), or new HTML being returned.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In the case where HTML is returned by the server, JavaScript on the client updates a partial area of the DOM (Document Object Model).
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] When raw data is returned, JavaScript on the client translates it into HTML using XSL or a JSON template before updating the DOM.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] A SPA moves logic from the server to the client, with the role of the web server evolving into a pure data API or web service.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This architectural shift has, in some circles, been coined "Thin Server Architecture" to highlight that complexity has been moved from the server to the client, with the argument that this ultimately reduces overall complexity of the system.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] The server keeps the necessary state in memory of the client state of the page.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In this way, when any request hits the server (usually user actions), the server sends the appropriate HTML and/or JavaScript with the concrete changes to bring the client to the new desired state (usually adding/deleting/updating a part of the client DOM).
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] At the same time, the state in server is updated.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Most of the logic is executed on the server, and HTML is usually also rendered on the server.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In some ways, the server simulates a web browser, receiving events and performing delta changes in server state which are automatically propagated to client.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This is a variant of the stateful server approach.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] The client page sends data representing its current state to the server, usually through Ajax requests.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This approach requires that more data be sent to the server and may require more computational resources per request to partially or fully reconstruct the client page state in the server.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] At the same time, this approach is more easily scalable because there is no per-client page data kept in the server and, therefore, Ajax requests can be dispatched to different server nodes with no need for session data sharing or server affinity.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Some SPAs may be executed from a local file using the file URI scheme.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This gives users the ability to download the SPA from a server and run the file from a local storage device, without depending on server connectivity.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] If such a SPA wants to store and update data, it must use browser-based Web Storage.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] These applications benefit from advances available with HTML.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Because the SPA is an evolution away from the stateless page-redraw model that browsers were originally designed for, some new challenges have emerged.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Because of the lack of JavaScript execution on crawlers of some popular Web search engines, SEO (search engine optimization) has historically presented a problem for public facing websites wishing to adopt the SPA model.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Between 2009 and 2015, Google Webmaster Central proposed and then recommended an "AJAX crawling scheme" using an initial exclamation mark in fragment identifiers for stateful AJAX pages (`#!`).
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Special behavior must be implemented by the SPA site to allow extraction of relevant metadata by the search engine's crawler.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] For search engines that do not support this URL hash scheme, the hashed URLs of the SPA remain invisible.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] These "hash-bang" URIs have been considered problematic by a number of writers including Jeni Tennison at the W3C because they make pages inaccessible to those who do not have JavaScript activated in their browser.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] They also break HTTP referer headers as browsers are not allowed to send the fragment identifier in the Referer header.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In 2015, Google deprecated their hash-bang AJAX crawling proposal.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Alternatively, applications may render the first page load on the server and subsequent page updates on the client.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This is traditionally difficult, because the rendering code might need to be written in a different language or framework on the server and in the client.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Using logic-less templates, cross-compiling from one language to another, or using the same language on the server and the client may help to increase the amount of code that can be shared.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In 2018, Google introduced dynamic rendering as another option for sites wishing to offer crawlers a non-JavaScript heavy version of a page for indexing purposes.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Dynamic rendering switches between a version of a page that is rendered client-side and a pre-rendered version for specific user agents.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This approach involves your web server detecting crawlers (via the user agent) and routing them to a renderer, from which they are then served a simpler version of HTML content.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] As of 2024, Google no longer recommends dynamic rendering, suggesting "server-side rendering, static rendering, or hydration" instead.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Because SEO compatibility is not trivial in SPAs, SPAs are commonly not used in a context where search engine indexing is either a requirement, or desirable.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Use cases include applications that surface private data hidden behind an authentication system.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In the cases where these applications are consumer products, often a classic "page redraw" model is used for the applications landing page and marketing site, which provides enough meta data for the application to appear as a hit in a search engine query.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Blogs, support forums, and other traditional page redraw artifacts often sit around the SPA that can seed search engines with relevant terms.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] As of 2021 and Google specifically, SEO compatibility for a plain SPA is straightforward and requires just a few simple conditions to be met.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] One way to increase the amount of code that can be shared between servers and clients is to use a logic-less template language like Mustache or Handlebars.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Such templates can be rendered from different host languages, such as Ruby on the server and JavaScript in the client.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] However, merely sharing templates typically requires duplication of business logic used to choose the correct templates and populate them with data.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Rendering from templates may have negative performance effects when only updating a small portion of the page—such as the value of a text input within a large template.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Replacing an entire template might also disturb a user's selection or cursor position, where updating only the changed value might not.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] To avoid these problems, applications can use UI data bindings or granular DOM manipulation to only update the appropriate parts of the page instead of re-rendering entire templates.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] With a SPA being, by definition, "a single page", the model breaks the browser's design for page history navigation using the "forward" or "back" buttons.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This presents a usability impediment when a user presses the back button, expecting the previous screen state within the SPA, but instead, the application's single page unloads and the previous page in the browser's history is presented.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] The traditional solution for SPAs has been to change the browser URL's hash fragment identifier in accord with the current screen state.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This can be achieved with JavaScript, and causes URL history events to be built up within the browser.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] As long as the SPA is capable of resurrecting the same screen state from information contained within the URL hash, the expected back-button behavior is retained.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] To further address this issue, the HTML specification has introduced pushState and replaceState providing programmatic access to the actual URL and browser history.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Analytics tools such as Google Analytics rely heavily upon entire new pages loading in the browser, initiated by a new page load.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] After the first page load, all subsequent page and content changes are handled internally by the application, which should simply call a function to update the analytics package.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Failing to call such a function, the browser never triggers a new page load, nothing gets added to the browser history, and the analytics package has no idea who is doing what on the site.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Similarly to the problems encountered with search engine crawlers, DAST tools may struggle with these JavaScript-rich applications.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Problems can include the lack of hypertext links, memory usage concerns and resources loaded by the SPA typically being made available by an Application Programming Interface or API.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Single-page applications are still subject to the same security risks as traditional web pages such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), but also a host of other unique vulnerabilities such as data exposure via API and client-side logic and client-side enforcement of server-side security.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In order to effectively scan a single-page application, a DAST scanner must be able to navigate the client-side application in a reliable and repeatable manner to allow discovery of all areas of the application and interception of all requests that the application sends to remote servers (e.g.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] It is possible to add page load events to a SPA using the HTML History API; this will help integrate analytics.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] The difficulty comes in managing this and ensuring that everything is being tracked accurately – this involves checking for missing reports and double entries.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Some frameworks provide free analytics integrations addressing most of the major analytics providers.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Developers can integrate them into the application and make sure that everything is working correctly, but there is no need to do everything from scratch.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] There are some ways of speeding up the initial load of a SPA, such as selective prerendering of the SPA landing/index page, caching and various code splitting techniques including lazy-loading modules when needed.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] But it's not possible to get away from the fact that it needs to download the framework, at least some of the application code; and will hit an API for data if the page is dynamic.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] This is a "pay me now, or pay me later" trade-off scenario.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] The question of performance and wait-times remains a decision that the developer must make.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] A SPA is fully loaded in the initial page load and then page regions are replaced or updated with new page fragments loaded from the server on demand.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] To avoid excessive downloading of unused features, a SPA will often progressively download more features as they become required, either small fragments of the page, or complete screen modules.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] In this way an analogy exists between "states" in a SPA and "pages" in a traditional website.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] Because "state navigation" in the same page is analogous to page navigation, in theory, any page-based web site could be converted to single-page replacing in the same page only the changed parts.
[src:elm-lang/single-page-application] The SPA approach on the web is similar to the single-document interface (SDI) presentation technique popular in native desktop applications.
